{"title_page": "Marie Rose sauce", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|article|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Marie Rose sauce\n| image            = Crab meat in shell with salad and Marie Rose sauce.jpg\n| caption          = [[Crab meat]] in shell with salad and Marie Rose sauce.\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[United Kingdom]]\n| region           = \n| creator          = [[Fanny Cradock]]\n| course           = \n| type             = [[condiment]]\n| served           = cold\n| main_ingredient  = tomatoes, [[mayonnaise]], [[Worchestershire sauce|Worcestershire sauce]], lemon juice and pepper\n| variations       = ketchup\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n\n[[File:Frysauce.JPG|thumb|right|260px|Fry sauce, similar in composition and appearance to Marie Rose sauce, served with french fries in the United States]]\n'''Marie Rose sauce''' (known in some areas as '''[[cocktail sauce]]''' or '''seafood sauce''') is a British  [[condiment]] often made from a blend of [[tomato]]es, [[mayonnaise]], [[Worchestershire sauce|Worcestershire sauce]], lemon juice and [[black pepper]]. A simpler version can be made by merely mixing tomato [[ketchup]] with mayonnaise. The sauce was popularised in the 1960s by British [[celebrity chef]] [[Fanny Cradock]].<ref name=C4>{{cite web|title=The origins of 10 modern classic foods |url=http://www.channel4.com/4food/features/top-10s/the-origins-of-10-modern-classic-foods |website=Channel 4 |accessdate=6 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406193543/http://www.channel4.com/4food/features/top-10s/the-origins-of-10-modern-classic-foods |archivedate=April 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIt is often accompanied with [[seafood]], and [[prawn]]s in particular.<ref>\"Prawn cocktail with Marie Rose sauce\" by John Torode, from the [[Celebrity MasterChef]], website: [https://www.bbc.com/food/recipes/prawn_cocktail_with_13755 https://www.bbc.com/food/recipes/prawn_cocktail_with_13755], accessed 2018</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nThe sauce is often credited to [[Fanny Cradock]] who certainly made it widely known; but variations exist internationally, and seafood cocktail sauces predate her 1967 recipe by some years. For example, [[Constance Spry]] published a recipe for Tomato Ice, a chilled mixture of mayonnaise and sweetened tomato pulp, in 1956 for use as the base of a prawn cocktail.<ref name=\"spry\">{{cite web |last1=Spry |first1=Constance |title=The Constance Spry Cookery Book |url=https://cookingbythebook.com/cookbook-reviews/cookbook-review-with-a-recipe-the-constance-spry-cookery-book-from-1956/ |website=Cooking by the Book |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe American [[cocktail sauce]] is a horseradish and ketchup-based sauce that is served with seafood, and dates back considerably earlier. Although this is not the same sauce as Marie Rose it is served in the same distinctive style in a prawn or shrimp cocktail; and it has been suggested that US cocktail sauce, made milder for British tastes, was the precursor of Marie Rose sauce.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Davis |first1=Jassy |title=Retro classics: The prawn cocktail |url=https://www.lovefood.com/news/58830/retro-classics-the-prawn-cocktail |website=lovefood.com |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe connection with the name Marie Rose is also not clear. Cradock is sometimes credited with the name, or there is an association with the British warship the [[Mary Rose]]. However the Mary Rose Trust itself has debunked this, saying \"As we still have a number of divers on our team who were around during this period, so we can ask them. Not one of them has any recollection of this happening... since the Mary Rose was in the news a lot during this period, it becomes clear that some people did the sums and came up with a nice story to justify the result.\"<ref name=\"maryrose\">{{cite web |title=Myths of the Mary Rose |url=https://maryrose.org/blog/historical/museum-blogger/myths-of-the-mary-rose/ |publisher=Mary Rose Trust |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Similar sauces==\n===United States===\nIn the United States, a similar sauce, [[fry sauce]], is sometimes served with french fries. Another similar sauce called [[Thousand Island dressing]] is popular in the United States and Canada. The Thousand Island dressing recipe reputedly originated from the [[Thousand Islands]] between the state of New York and the province of Ontario.<ref>[http://whatscookingamerica.net/Sauces_Condiments/ThousandIslandDressing.htm]</ref> In Argentina, [[salsa golf]] is a similar sauce created in the 1920s at a golf course, hence the name.\n\n===Ireland===\nIn Ireland, Marie Rose sauce ({{lang-ga|anlann Marie-Rose}}) refers primarily to just ketchup and mayonnaise, and often salt and pepper. Marie Rose sauce in chip shops is usually known as \"'''burger sauce'''\", though there are many names in use. However, the above British versions are also used in Ireland. The name used is dependent on where it is being served (e.g. chip shop) and what the sauce is being accompanied with (such as chips or salad). More formal recipes may also incorporate ingredients such as [[horseradish]], herbs, and a splash of Irish [[brandy]].\n\nSome restaurants may top or accompany Marie Rose sauce with Irish [[cheddar cheese]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cocktail sauce]]\n* [[Dip (food)#List of common dips|List of dips]]\n* [[List of sauces]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [http://www.marthastewart.com/recipe/marie-rose-sauce Marie Rose sauce] recipe\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/coventry/content/articles/2005/12/05/christmas_recipes_feature.shtml BBC - recipe includes a description of Marie Rose sauce]\n\n{{Condiments}}\n\n{{portal bar|Food}}\n\n[[Category:Condiments]]\n[[Category:British condiments]]\n[[Category:Fish products]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|article|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Marie Rose sauce\n| image            = C